<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-966-438  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 966 438.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Dec 11 1989 v8 n25 p43(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Military use of fiber optics to increase 26% annually.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Masud, S.A.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Market Intelligence Research Co. (reports).andO;Topic:     Fiber OpticsMilitaryStudyMarket ShareOutlook.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Military Use of Fiber Optics to Increase 26% AnnuallyandM;The use of optical fiber by the military will increase at an average annualrate of 26 percent through the middle of the 1990s, a recent report said.andM;The overall military market for the medium will total a modest $261.87million in 1994, a study by Market Intelligence Research Co. estimated.andM;The study pegged the size of the military fiber-optic market last year at $52million and projected an increase to $65 million by the end of this year.andO;&quot;It's a small market and perhaps there's been some hyperbole about it,&quot; saidBruce Tolley, research manager for the Mountain View, Calif., company.andM;Perhaps the biggest increase in fiber-optic components will be in tacticalapplications, with the compound annual growth rate exceeding 35 percentduring the period from 1988 to 1994, the study said.andM;&quot;The largest tactical applications for fiber optics in the military is forplatform command, control, communications and intelligence, avionics,navigation, and electronic warfare systems,&quot; it said.andM;Use of fiber optics in military aircraft applications is forecast to increase46 percent annually.andP;  Military aircraft are expected to make extensive use ofoptical fiber in high-speed data buses, line replaceable modules andintegrated optical connectors in programs such as the IntegratedCommunications, Navigation, Identification Avionics; Modular Avionics SystemArchitecture; and Advanced Digital/Optical Control System, the study said.andM;The second largest fiber-optic application will be ground-laid cable.andP;  It isprojected to increase 30 percent annually as the benefits of the mediumcreate demand in ground-laid cable applications, the study said.andM;Though longer wavelengths are expected to result in greater use ofsingle-mode fiber and laser transmitters, the study noted that the cost oflong wavelength data links is generally three times higher than the cost ofshort wavelengths.andM;The Fiber Distributed Data Interface standard for networking over single-modefiber, coupled with the slow development of single-mode component standardsand problems with lasers in harsh environments, have delayed the penetrationof single-mode fiber in the tactical applications market, the study said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>